items.title: Fancy Tiger Crafts
items.description: Fancy Tiger is a shop in Denver specializing in craft supplies and classes for the modern crafter. Since 2006 they've gone from a tiny storefront in south Denver to a large store in the heart of the city with a full-blown e-commerce presence. As their business continues to grow, so must their web store. I teamed up with a designer to revamp the design and improve all aspects of user experience. The site is built on Shopify so the majority of my work here utilizes Javascript, Liquid and SASS to craft solutions within some pretty tight boundaries. Moving forward, my thought is that Fancy Tiger is outgrowing Shopify and a platform change is necessary, but we do our best with what we inherit.

items.title: One Floor Up
items.description: One Floor Up is a video and motion graphics production company in Denver who sorely needed an updated web presence. I teamed up with Wonder Giant to build them a fresh experience. Their shiny new site is built on Wordpress so this project was a nice mix of Javascript, PHP and SASS. The biggest challenge here was creating the UX for the unconventional layouts and navigation. Nothing a little flex-box and javascript can't solve!

items.title: Arbonne
items.description: I worked with Arbonne for the better part of 2016 helping them develop modern ways to communicate with customers and sell their products.

sub1.title: Arbonne Screen
sub1.description: This touchscreen app leverages Arbonne's API to showcase the company and its vast array of products in a fun, interactive way. This particular iteration was deployed on a large screen in a Taiwanese airport.

sub2.title: React Shopping Cart
sub2.description: A fully functional shopping cart proof-of-concept built using React, Redux and Arbonne's own API.

sub3.title: Arbot
sub3.description: 'Arbot' is a Facebook Messenger bot built on Node and Express using the Messenger Platform Send API and wit.ai. Once a link is established between a users Arbonne account and their Facebook account, the bot can suggest recommended items, fetch order info and even process orders without leaving Messenger.

items.title: The Wonderment
items.blockquote: In the Wonderment, kids participate in collaborative creative experiences with other kids across the globe and turn their shared imagination and interaction into a currency backed by brands and donors to support social good projects benefitting kids around the world. Itâ€™s a place where kids can find their creative voice, connect it to others and use it to make a difference.
items.description: I worked with the fine folks over at Wonder Giant on this project and while the work I did is hidden from the public-facing side of the site, it's a great project so head on over and check it out!

imgsSeq.title: Avatar customization
imgsSeq.caption: Users are able to customize their avatar by purchasing outfits with points earned through participation.

Users earn points for every action they take on the site. Once they earn enough points to 'level up,' they earn a new badge and a notification lets them know how awesome they are. Publicly visible achievement levels offer a source of pride and promotes further interaction.

items.title: Comments Are the Best
items.description: I always find it entertaining reading through comments around the web, especially when the subject matter gets a little controversial. This novelty app is essentially a robot that vocalizes the musings and opinions of YouTube users, removing any emotion in the messages with its monotonous voices. It utilizes YouTube Player, YouTube Data and Speech Synthesis APIs to fetch and read back comments from videos. Videos or playlists can be retrieved by keyword search, channel search, manual id entry or video category. The original idea for this project was ultra simple but, ya know, things escalated quickly and I'm still trying to figure out if it's funny or just plain annoying =)

items.title: Insight
items.description: AIMS (Advanced Intelligence Management System) is a risk-analysis tool that allows companies to visualize threats to their assets in real time. Using data gathered about incidents all over the world - everything from armed robberies to earthquakes - users can easily visualize which of these events might cause problems. They are then able to make logistical adjustments in order to maximize efficiency of assets. AIMS is built on ExtJS, is fully customizable with an administrative tool and currently has 3 different themes.

items.title: Baby Blu
items.description: Baby Blu Organics sorely needed a re-design so I took it on as a side-project. It's a pretty straightforward E-commerce site built on WordPress and Woocommerce. The theme is a spin-off of Uplift, a fine theme from the folks at Swift Ideas.

items.title: Fogged Clarity
items.description: I co-founded the arts review Fogged Clarity in 2009 and it's become a mainstay in both my creative and technical development. As a venue for visual art, music, interviews, fiction and poetry it has provided me with a way to continually improve my chops across the board. Design, development, audio & video editing, podcasting and brand development are just a few of the things I handle on a regular basis. It has been the unmoving rock that I use to learn new things, test new technologies and keep myself honest. Fogged Clarity is built on WordPress using a custom theme that turns the CMS into an issue-based publication and allows editors to do as much as possible without my help.

items.title: Acura
items.description: I spent six months in 2015 working on the Acura account building rich media. Some of this time was spent working on the full-screen mobile experience found below. The unit touts the safety of Acura vehicles and was launched as a single piece of a larger campaign.

sub1.title: MotoX Color Picker
sub1.description: With Motorola's launch of the Moto X, we were tasked with creating rich media that would mimic the functionality of the 'MotoMaker' website. One of the main selling points of the Moto X was the vast array of colors with which users could customize the device. I was able to condense that functionality into rich media units that were featured on YouTube and elsewhere.

sub2.title: MotoX Mood Skin
sub2.description: This 'Mood Skin' consisted of full-page background imagery that synced with an in-page banner.

sub3.title: MotoX All-in-One Media
sub3.description: This is one example of the many rich media units I built while on the Moto account.

items.title: Divvy Bike Share Data Viz
items.description: Divvy is Chicago's bike sharing service. While at Razorfish, we put together a team to create an entry for the 'Divvy Data Challenge.' I ended up swamped with client work and was unable to continue with the official submission, but afterwards I continued building my idea. This demo shows incoming and outgoing data from Divvy stations over a period of 24 hours. I utilized Leaflet and d3.js for the data projection and GSAP for animation. I've narrowed down the data set to a single day (July 4th, 2013) for the purposes of demonstration and performance. Clear patterns emerge showing that some stations have disproportionate incoming or outgoing traffic.

items.title: rydaly.com v1
items.description: Version one of my site, recently retired. I wanted to keep it ultra-fast and simple, so much of the work I did here is under the hood, hand-coded and lean.

items.title: Samsung
items.description: Upon launch of the Galaxy S4, we created a blitz of ads and interactive experiences.

sub1.title: Galaxy S4 YouTube Masthead
sub1.description: Three different versions of this ad ran on YouTube over the period of a week. Other versions were then adapted for a litany of other sites.

sub2.title: Galaxy S4 Eraser Race
sub2.description: Loads of fun working on this one. It's an in-banner mini game highlighting the cutting edge technologies of the Galaxy S4.

items.title: Blackberry
items.description: Blackberry was my first long-term project as a professional. Looking back, it's clear now that the work I did here fortified my passion for interactive media.

sub1.title: New York Times 'Blackout' Takeover
sub1.description: This ad required custom components that didn't even exist before the project. I worked closely with developers at DoubleClick to make it work. It took some doing, but eventually launched and caused quite a controversy. Though, I think the controversy had more to do with Blackberry's claim that 'Amateur Hour is Over.'

sub2.title: Blackberry Brand Botiques
sub2.description: Hosted on sites like Best Buy and Walmart, these units were in constant need of updating and maintenance. A good example of why building something right the first time really helps in the long run.

sub3.title: Heart & Head Rich Media
sub3.description: An example of the typical drama and elegance we were striving for.

items.title: Cambodia Law & Policy Journal
items.description: CLPJ is a niche law journal targeted at those interested in the prosecution of Khmer Rouge war criminals in Cambodia. I was honored to have been asked to create a venue for them to share progress on these on-going issues in Cambodia. They needed a venue where they could publish their quarterly journal and publish a blog with absolutely no help from me. The journal is built on WordPress with a custom theme.
